[[Image:Akbar_Ali_Khan.GIF||frame|Dr. Akbar Ali Khan]]

'''Akbar Ali Khan''' ({{lang-bn|<U+0986><U+0995><U+09AC><U+09B0> <U+0986><U+09B2><U+09BF> <U+0996><U+09BE><U+09A8>}}) is a Bangladeshi [[economist]] and [[educationist]] who served as a [[bureaucrat]] until 2001. He was the SDO of [[Habiganj]] during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]], when he decided to join the war. Later he became involved with the [[Mujibnagar Government]]. After the independence he joined back the civil service and also worked as a university teacher. Towards the end of 2006, he became one of the advisers of the [[Caretaker Government of Bangladesh|Caretaker Government]] for a brief period which was led by President [[Iajuddin Ahmed]]. In October 2007, the [[Government of Bangladesh]] constituted a Regulatory Reforms Commission with him as the chair. 

== Early life ==
Akbar Ali was born in Nabinagar, [[Brahmanbaria]]. He spend his whole school life in Nabinagar High School. He got admitted to the [[Dhaka College]] and passed I. Sc. (now HSC) from there in 1961. The he studies history at the [[University of Dhaka]] and completed his Bachelors and Masters from there in 1964 and 1965 respectively, with first class, topping list on both the occasions. Before joining the then [[CSP|Civil Service of Pakistan]] he served as a teacher for some time. After foundation course at the Civil Service Academy in [[Lahore]] (1967-68), he was posted as the sub-divisional officer (SDO)  of now defunct sub-district [[Habiganj]] in 1969.<ref name="Akbar">{{Citation
  | last=Zakaria
  | first=A. K. M.
